  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- These provide global standards and guidelines for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Enable cross-border cooperation in investigating and prosecuting financial crimes\n- Facilitate information sharing between countries\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Countries must implement international standards into their national legal frameworks\n- Requires consistent anti-money laundering (AML) regulations and reporting mechanisms\n\n4. Financial Institution Regulations\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international compliance standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) and suspicious transaction reporting requirements\n\n5. Jurisdictional Enforcement\n- Countries coordinate to track and prosecute complex transnational money laundering operations\n- Extradition agreements support cross-border legal proceedings\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International bodies can impose economic sanctions on countries with weak AML regulations\n- Potential financial and diplomatic consequences for non-compliance\n\n7. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Global databases and communication networks\n- Enhanced tracking of suspicious financial transactions\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating money laundering internationally.",
